{"id":"2112.12778","submitter":"Philip Easo","authors":"Philip Easo and Tom Hutchcroft","title":"Supercritical percolation on finite transitive graphs I: Uniqueness of\n  the giant component","comments":"43 pages. Proof of the bounded degree case in the first 25 pages","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.PR math-ph math.CO math.MP","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Let $(G_n)_{n \\geq 1} = ((V_n,E_n))_{n \\geq 1}$ be a sequence of finite,\nconnected, vertex-transitive graphs with volume tending to infinity. We say\nthat a sequence of parameters $(p_n)_{n \\geq 1}$ in $[0,1]$ is supercritical\nwith respect to Bernoulli bond percolation $\\mathbb{P}_p^G$ if there exists\n$\\varepsilon >0$ and $N<\\infty$ such that \\[\n  \\mathbb{P}_{(1-\\varepsilon)p_n}^{G_n} \\big( \\text{the largest cluster\ncontains at least $\\varepsilon |V_n|$ vertices}\\big) \\geq \\varepsilon \\qquad\n\\text{ for every $n\\geq N$.} \\] We prove that if $(G_n)_{n \\geq 1}$ is sparse,\nmeaning that the degrees are sublinear in the number of vertices, then the\nsupercritical giant cluster is unique with high probability in the sense that\nif $(p_n)_{n \\geq 1}$ is supercritical then \\[\n  \\lim_{n\\to\\infty}\\mathbb{P}_{p_n}^{G_n} \\big( \\text{the second largest\ncluster contains at least $c|V_n|$ vertices} \\big) = 0 \\qquad \\text{ for every\n$c>0$.} \\] This result is new even under the stronger hypothesis that $(G_n)_{n\n\\geq 1}$ has uniformly bounded vertex degrees, in which case it verifies a\nconjecture of Benjamini (2001). Previous work of many authors had established\nthe same theorem for complete graphs, torii, hypercubes, and bounded degree\nexpander graphs, each using methods that are highly specific to the examples\nthey treated. We also give a complete solution to the problem of supercritical\nuniqueness for dense vertex-transitive graphs, establishing a simple necessary\nand sufficient isoperimetric condi